<h3>Pilot clinics</h3>

<p>Five pilot gender services have been running since 2020-21, intended to reduce pressure on legacy GICs. In practice, they have shorter lists but limited capacity and are not yet fully operational replacements.</p>

<h3>"Waiting Well" initiative</h3>

<p>NHS England is piloting a "Waiting Well" programme from early 2026 in the south-west region, offering limited support to people on waiting lists. Details are sparse and it has not yet launched nationally.</p>

<h2>Scotland</h2>

<p>Scotland publishes waiting time data through Public Health Scotland. The numbers are grim:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Glasgow (Sandyford)</strong>: Effectively a <strong>224-year theoretical wait</strong> based on current throughput versus list size. 98% of people waiting 3+ years are at this clinic.</li>
  <li><strong>Edinburgh (Chalmers)</strong>: Shorter but still measured in years.</li>
  <li>510 people have been waiting 3-4 years, 601 waiting 4-5 years, 167 waiting 5+ years.</li>
</ul>

<p>The Scottish Government target is 18 weeks from referral to first appointment. No gender clinic is anywhere close to meeting this.</p>

<p class="source">Source: <a href="https://publichealthscotland.scot/publications/nhs-gender-identity-clinics-waiting-times-for-first-outpatient-consultation/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Public Health Scotland — NHS Gender Identity Clinics Waiting Times (Oct 2025)</a></p>

<h2>Wales</h2>

<p>Wales has a single Welsh Gender Service. Average waiting times are around <strong>2 years</strong>, significantly better than England and Scotland but still far beyond the 18-week target. Public data is more limited.</p>

<h2>Northern Ireland</h2>

<p>Northern Ireland's Brackenburn Clinic in Belfast is the sole provider. Waiting times are comparable to English clinics. Cross-border access to services in the Republic of Ireland is theoretically possible but poorly established.</p>

<h2>What the community says</h2>

<p>There is no disagreement on this topic. Across every community space — Reddit, forums, TikTok, focus groups — the consensus is the same:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Waiting times are dangerous and people are suffering.</li>
  <li>The system is not fit for purpose.</li>
  <li>Most people are forced into private care or self-medication because they cannot wait 5-12 years.</li>
  <li>Some people report being on waiting lists for years without receiving <strong>any</strong> contact from the clinic.</li>
</ul>

<blockquote>
  "I've had no support at all... from any kind of professional. It's been 5 years since I applied to the gender clinic."
  <br /><em>— Focus group participant, Dec 2025</em>
</blockquote>

<h2>What are the alternatives?</h2>

<p>While waiting for NHS services, most trans people in the UK use one or more of the following:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Private providers:</strong> GenderGP (no waiting list, ~£195 setup + monthly subscription), GenderCare (~£600 initial, ~5 month wait), London Transgender Clinic (~£1,060 for first 2 years, &lt;1 month wait). See our upcoming <em>UK private providers compared</em> topic.</li>
  <li><strong>Bridging prescriptions:</strong> Your GP <em>can</em> prescribe HRT as a bridging measure while you wait. Many won't, but some will — especially with guidance from a private provider. This is explicitly supported by NHS policy but inconsistently applied.</li>
  <li><strong>Self-medication:</strong> Approximately 25% of trans people in the UK self-medicate with hormones obtained online. This is a harm reduction reality driven by system failure, not a preference. See <a href="https://transharmreduction.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Trans Harm Reduction</a> for safety information.</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout callout-pink">
  <p><strong>You are not stuck.</strong> Being on an NHS waiting list does not mean doing nothing for years. Private providers, bridging prescriptions, and informed self-advocacy are options. We'll be covering each of these in dedicated topics.</p>
</div>

